ntsb4127txt-1-5-5-0-6 Visual meteorological conditions prevailed for the 14 Code of Federal Regulations Part 135 on-demand air taxi flight, and a company visual flight rules (VFR) flight plan was filed. 
ntsb4127txt-1-5-5-0-3 On August 24, 2001, at 0715 central daylight time, a Bell 206L-3 helicopter, N350AL, was destroyed when it impacted water during an emergency descent in the Gulf of Mexico, 6 miles south of Cameron, Louisiana. 
ntsb4127txt-1-5-5-0-4 The helicopter was registered to and operated by Air Logistics LLC, of New Iberia, Louisiana. 
ntsb4127txt-1-5-5-0-11 The pilot attempted to decelerate the helicopter; however, the controls became stiff and, subsequently, the helicopter "hit the water hard."According to Air Logistics personnel, the helicopter's engine and airframe, with exception of the tail boom from the horizontal stabilizer rearward, was recovered to a secure facility in New Iberia, Louisiana. 
ntsb4127txt-1-5-5-0-1 This is preliminary information, subject to change, and may contain errors. 
ntsb4127txt-1-5-5-0-7 The flight originated from the Air Logistics Heliport, Cameron, Louisiana, and was destined for West Cameron 149, an offshore oil platform located in the Gulf of Mexico. 
ntsb4127txt-1-5-5-0-5 The commercial pilot and his one passenger sustained serious injuries. 
ntsb4127txt-1-5-5-0-9 He lowered the collective control and the engine "quit." 
ntsb4127txt-1-5-5-0-10 An autorotation was initiated and the floats were deployed. 
ntsb4127txt-1-5-5-0-8 According to the pilot, the helicopter was in cruise flight when the it began to "vibrate and shudder." 
